  "prompt": "Why do Hindu people hate Dr. B. R. Ambedkar?",
  "response": "It is not accurate to say that all Hindu people hate Dr. B. R. Ambedkar. Dr. Ambedkar was a pivotal figure in Indian history, known for his role in drafting the Indian Constitution and his fight against social discrimination and untouchability. He was himself born into a Dalit family, which is considered to be at the lower end of the caste hierarchy in Hinduism.\n\nHowever, there are some individuals and groups within the Hindu community who may have negative views about Dr. Ambedkar due to various reasons:\n\n1. **Caste System Critique**: Dr. Ambedkar was a fierce critic of the caste system and worked tirelessly to eradicate untouchability. Some orthodox Hindus who support or are less critical of the caste system may view his efforts as an attack on traditional Hindu social structures.\n\n2. **Conversion to Buddhism**: Dr. Ambedkar converted to Buddhism and encouraged many Dalits to do the same as a means to escape the oppressive caste system. This act may have been seen as a rejection of Hinduism by some Hindus.\n\n3. **Political Differences**: Dr. Ambedkar's political views and actions sometimes put him at odds with other political leaders and groups, including some Hindu nationalist organizations. These political tensions can lead to negative perceptions of him among certain groups.\n\nIt's important to recognize that these views do not represent all Hindus. Many Hindus respect and admire Dr. Ambedkar for his contributions to social justice and the Indian Constitution. Additionally, his work has had a significant impact on improving the lives of millions of Dalits and other marginalized communities in India.",
